Yes, I know this is also a rather unorthodox choice for a Halloween marathon, but screw it, it has a scene that takes place during Halloween, so I say it counts. Besides, it makes perfect sense to revisit Nicole Kidman‚Äôs first foray into the DC Universe with Aquaman coming out later this year, doesn‚Äôt it? So here we are at last ‚Äì Batman Forever. The one Batman movie that I had never seen in its entirety until now. And I‚Äôm not gonna beat around the bush, guys ‚Äì out of all the live action Batman movies this is by far my least favorite. You can argue all you want that Batman & Robin is worse, but at least that movie had a more consistent tone, it committed to its campy batshit insanity and at least there was more of an awareness of what they were doing and the type of movie they were making. Joel Schumacher once said that everybody involved with Batman Forever was very reluctant to work on it and let me tell you, the behind-the-scenes problems are very evident in the final product. This is the most tonally confused DC movie I‚Äôve seen pre-Justice League. Warner Bros. wanted to lighten things up and take the series in a more family friendly direction after Batman Returns, but the film still has some pretty dark and serious moments and it‚Äôs clear that Schumacher had a very hard time balancing those completely opposite elements, leading to some pretty jarring tonal shifts. Don‚Äôt misunderstand me ‚Äì the scenes between Alfred and Bruce in Batman & Robin (AKA the best parts of it) also clashed with the overall campy and silly tone of the movie, but in hindsight, even they weren‚Äôt this jarring. Oh, and you just gotta love how the studio was constantly going on and on and on about how they were taking things in a more family friendly direction, yet they still allowed the early dialogue exchanges between Chase Meridian and Batman, a close-up of Batman‚Äôs ass and a Nicole Kidman panty shot. I‚Äôd really like to know how Schumacher blackmailed WB to let him keep the latter two in the final cut. And trust me, the uneven tone of this movie is the least of its problems, but before I move on, I‚Äôll just like to take this moment to say that Batman Forever‚Äôs title sequence is hands down the worst in the franchise ‚Äì the cast‚Äôs names flying out at us against a boring-ass black backdrop via effects that even Power Point presentations would laugh at. How fucking inspired. Say what you will about the other Batman movies, but they knew how to introduce their titles. The first Burton movie had the camera circling through a huge Batman logo. Batman Returns showed us the origin of the Penguin as the credits were rolling. And in both cases we had Danny Elfman‚Äôs epic Batman theme blaring in the background, perfectly complementing the visuals. Even Batman & Robin got this right! www.youtube.com/watch?v=xP4WLAeOpyM And now that I‚Äôve made my point, let‚Äôs continue. The movie‚Äôs chaotic production is also reflected in its storytelling, which is really poor in some areas, more particularly with regard to some of the characters, especially Two-Face. Harvey Dent is one of the most tragic Batman villains of all time, so much so that his fall from grace and his transformation into Two-Face was a major central storyline in The Dark Knight and the brilliant way it was handled is one of the many reasons why that movie is held in such high regard. Sadly, Batman Forever not only glosses over this tragedy which can fill an entire movie on its own (or at the very least be an intricate part of a much larger storyline), reducing it to really clumsy exposition dumps, but it turns Two-Face into a complete joke. I am not exaggerating in the slightest when I say that he literally has no reason whatsoever to hate Batman in this movie. Batman wasn‚Äôt the one who threw acid in his face ‚Äì it was a mob boss! Why doesn‚Äôt he hate and try to kill that mob boss?! Especially since that‚Äôs exactly what he did in the Batman: The Animated Series two-parter ‚ÄúTwo-Face‚Äù. Why? Because the writers of that show can actually think logically. The only reason he fought Batman in those two episodes was because Batman kept getting in his way. Aside from that, his attention was focused entirely on the man who ruined his life. They also try to give Batman and Two-Face a connection in this movie and they fail miserably at it ‚Äì towards the end Batman tells Two-Face that he was a good friend and it really doesn‚Äôt work because those two had zero connection in the previous two movies. Some people have actually tried to defend this, stating that Forever is actually a soft reboot, but this argument holds no weight because there are very overt references to the previous two movies and Pat Hingle and Michael Gough are still playing Commissioner Gordon and Alfred. But even taking that out of the equation, the connection between Batman and Two-Face that they so desperately try to push doesn‚Äôt work because we never saw them as friends. Compare that to Star Wars: A New Hope. In that film, Obi-Wan and Vader have only one scene together, but because of Obi-Wan‚Äôs earlier recounting of his tragic past experiences with Vader, you could feel the history and the connection between them, which is why their encounter is such an effective moment. On top of his total lack of motivation, Two-Face cannot even be considered a character because he is not a character ‚Äì he‚Äôs a plot device. The only reason why he‚Äôs in this movie is to pave the way for a connection and a relationship that actually works, but we‚Äôll get to that later. The rest of the time he‚Äôs mugging obnoxiously for the camera. Which brings me to the final reason this version of Two-Face doesn‚Äôt work ‚Äì Tommy Lee Jones‚Äô terrible performance. Jones is a great actor and he‚Äôs certainly had successful forays into the comic book movie genre (Men in Black, Captain America: The First Avenger), but here he is just embarrassing himself ‚Äì so much so that I can‚Äôt even say I feel sorry for him. This guy actually had the balls to criticize Jim Carrey‚Äôs performance and call him a buffoon. Motherfucker, did you ever stop to consider how YOU looked from the sidelines while making this movie? Unlike you, Carrey was actually entertaining and his Riddler actually had a personality, but again, let‚Äôs not get ahead of ourselves. And that piece of shit makeup you‚Äôre wearing is certainly not helping your case. I love Rick Baker, but he must have been high as a kite when he created that makeup. Can‚Äôt say I blame him. Guys, say what you will about Arnold Schwarzenegger‚Äôs Mr. Freeze, but at least he was a fleshed out character with fleshed out and understandable motives and he actually went through an arc. OK, I‚Äôm done talking about Two-Face, let‚Äôs move on because we still have a lot of ground to cover. Next up, we have another very problematic character ‚Äì Dr. Chase Meridian, played by Nicole Kidman. This has got to be the worst psychiatrist I‚Äôve ever seen in a movie because throughout a good chunk of her screentime all she does is talk about how she wants to bang Batman. Also, what psychiatrist does boxing before sessions with her patients? And to top it all off, I just don‚Äôt feel any chemistry between her and Val Kilmer, which makes the moment when Bruce decides to quit being Batman so he can be with her that much more unbelievable. Are you kidding me? This horny chick with a major Bat-boner is the reason why Bruce decides to quit being Batman?! Not the death of the Graysons. Not the fact that he failed to save Harvey Dent from becoming Two-Face. Not some crippling injury. They do try to give an explanation, but it comes across as incredibly half-assed. The sad thing is, this character actually could‚Äôve worked if they had made her a villain and called her Harleen Quinzel. Think about it ‚Äì Chase Meridian is a psychiatrist who is obsessed with one of Gotham‚Äôs most famous loonies (because, come on, what sane person would fight crime dressed up as a giant bat?) and wants to write a book on said loony and even become romantically involved with him. That‚Äôs literally note for note Harley Quinn‚Äôs character and if they had gotten rid of Two-Face, renamed her to Harleen Quinzel and focused on her obsession with Batman leading her to become Harley Quinn, modeling herself after the Joker, we could‚Äôve had something there. I mean, she‚Äôs gotta know about the Joker and the other villains Batman has fought (‚ÄúDo I need skin-tight vinyl and a whip?‚Äù), but I digress. But by far the character who really got the shaft in this movie is Commissioner Gordon. Now, I can‚Äôt pretend this is something exclusive to this movie because he was also pretty ineffectual in the Burton films, but here they really cranked up his useless levels to 11, as he just lets Batman do his job for him almost all the time. It just feels like a waste of Pat Hingle‚Äôs talents and it makes me all the more thankful for the much better way that Christopher Nolan and Gary Oldman portrayed Gordon. And at this point you‚Äôre probably wondering if there‚Äôs even anything I liked about this movie. Well, yes ‚Äì quite a few things, actually. For all its problems (and believe me, there are many more), the movie does have its fair share of redeeming qualities. First and foremost, The Riddler. What can I say ‚Äì Jim Carrey is always a plus and he is as entertaining and funny as he‚Äôs ever been and the manic energy he brings to the character really helps elevate this movie. Edward Nygma is pretty much the type of obsessive fan that Stephen King wrote about in Misery. Carrey perfectly rides the line between funny and psychotic and you understand why Nygma hates Bruce Wayne. Not to mention that his plan ‚Äì using mass media as a way to steal people‚Äôs knowledge and secrets ‚Äì is brilliant and has become even more relevant as a commentary in this day and age. Next up, we have the second best character in the movie ‚Äì Dick Grayson aka Robin. While Chris O‚ÄôDonnell does look way too old to be a teenager, he still does a pretty good job in the role, making you feel the pain that Robin is going through after losing his entire family, leading to some really well done interactions and conversations between him and Bruce. They can actually relate to each other because they lost their parents in a very similar fashion. I also have to give costume designers Ingrid Ferrin and Bob Ringwood credit because the Robin costume actually looks pretty damn good. The only issue I have with Robin is the way he was captured by Two-Face, which I don‚Äôt buy for a second. I mean, seriously, he couldn‚Äôt have just knocked the gun out of Two-Face‚Äôs hand? Jeez, Robin, sometimes you really are a D-I-C-K. Despite my issues with Chase, Nicole Kidman does fine with the material she‚Äôs given. Val Kilmer is‚Ä¶ OK as Batman, I guess, derpy Bat-smile notwithstanding. Nothing great, but nothing terrible. Like I said, his best scenes in this movie are with Dick and, to his credit, Val Kilmer does an admirable job portraying Bruce‚Äôs guilt for failing to save the Graysons as well as his psychological torment and PTSD. The extremely atmospheric way that Schumacher and DOP Stephen Goldblatt shot the death of the Waynes and Batman‚Äôs origin, is nothing short of breathtaking, especially that shot of the bat flying towards little Bruce. And last, but definitely not least, Michael Gough knocks it out of the park as Alfred once again. Production designer Barbara Ling also managed to craft some pretty impressive sets, especially Two-Face‚Äôs lair and Arkham Asylum, which looks really cool. It‚Äôs really sad when the lair of a villain has more character and personality than its master, but what can you do. Lastly, while I certainly understand why it‚Äôs not everybody‚Äôs cup of tea, I personally really enjoyed Elliot Goldenthal‚Äôs score. In conclusion, despite a few bright spots and a couple of well-adapted moments from the comics, Batman Forever is overall a mess, suffering from poorly developed characters, inconsistencies with the previous two movies, an uneven tone and some pretty cringe-worthy dialogue and moments. I know a lot of people really like it because it was their first introduction to Batman ‚Äì and if that‚Äôs the case, more power to you, go ahead and enjoy it, there‚Äôs certainly a lot to like about it ‚Äì but, as controversial as this may sound, in my opinion Batman & Robin is better. It‚Äôs not a good movie by any means, but it had more of an identity, it was more self-aware and at least it went all the way with its campy schlock. If Batman Forever is on TV, I might watch it, but I‚Äôd rather have a DVD/Blu-Ray player remote so I can fast-forward to the good moments. On the bright side, at least now we know why Ace Ventura hates bats. Next time, on the Halloween marathon, we go from DC to Marvel because it‚Äôs open season on all suckheads. Stay tuned.
