Alexander Payne's unfairly maligned Downsizing has the rare storyline that you could almost have a more satisfying time listening to someone describe than actually seeing executed. This has always been the filmmaker Payne has been. His most cohesive films have everything in common with this heady, meandering and benign film. It would have been a savory novel were it not for the lovely visual gimmick of how people re-imagine space and civilization at five inches tall. And Downsizing elevates its gimmick: Even if we scoff and laugh at it, we realize that the way things are going, it's no crazier an idea than anything else we could desperately concoct in an attempt to escape our irreversible environmental fate. The social make-up fo the world as microcosm is certainly intriguing, a dollhouse of all the world's indulgences and hardships in one Russian doll. While Downsizing is not without concern for the end of human life on earth, it faces the threat with little gravitas, and instead meditates wryly on what ‚Äúthe good life‚Äù may comprise, here and now. A change of perspective helps one to better grasp the world, and Downsizing makes it as straightforward as an allegory can be without losing its luster in the first act.
