‚ÄúWe‚Äôre getting ourselves some liquid entertainment‚Äù Kathryn Bigelow‚Äôs debut feature feels very much like a debut ‚Äì it‚Äôs loose on plot, heavy on mood, low-budget and the first trembling touches upon themes the director would later explore more. Willem Dafoe (in his second role in his career) fits smoothly in this mold as well, but he doesn‚Äôt exactly breathe life into the silent biker-character we‚Äôve seen before. The same kind of character has also had more heavy themes tied to him in other films, Dafoe‚Äôs silent character is a good contrast to the macho group that‚Äôs often seen in biker-films but while he‚Äôs somewhat outside of that masculine heteronormative mold it‚Äôs never really explored. The Loveless has some great groovy music to bring the right kind of cool to everything and it fits the laidback, thin story. Unfortunately, the anonymous characters in the periphery of Dafoe is given too much of the spotlight as the film trades the nice silence for empty dialogue. It‚Äôs an interesting mood-piece as a start for Bigelow and Dafoe ‚Äì but with such thin jabs at themes the director would go on to explore much more it‚Äôs ultimately not very spectacular.
